1
00:00:02,932 --> 00:00:07,170
Other arguments include that the
preborn child is just a clump of cells,

2
00:00:07,170 --> 00:00:09,172
or that embryos pass through various

3
00:00:09,172 --> 00:00:12,308
evolutionary stages
on the way to becoming human.

4
00:00:12,308 --> 00:00:16,846
By that logic, one might be
aborting a fish or a reptile rather than a human.

5
00:00:16,846 --> 00:00:19,248
But that notion
comes from a long-discredited

6
00:00:19,248 --> 00:00:23,820
evolutionary argument based on
fraudulent drawings by Ernst Haeckel.

7
00:00:23,820 --> 00:00:28,558
While this idea may still show up in
an occasional biology, text, or online video,

8
00:00:28,558 --> 00:00:31,661
most evolutionists
know it's completely false.

9
00:00:31,661 --> 00:00:34,063
Even if it were
true, the notion that an embryo

10
00:00:34,063 --> 00:00:37,367
can be aborted while
it's in a fish or reptile state

11
00:00:37,367 --> 00:00:41,070
implies that it becomes more
valuable when it reaches human form.

12
00:00:41,070 --> 00:00:43,606
Well, this runs contrary to evolution.

13
00:00:43,606 --> 00:00:46,542
But what about the
so-called clump of cells?

14
00:00:46,542 --> 00:00:50,613
Even the first fertilized
egg has its own unique DNA code

15
00:00:50,613 --> 00:00:54,650
that's distinctly human
and different from both parents.

16
00:00:54,650 --> 00:00:56,686
So not the mother's body.

17
00:00:56,686 --> 00:00:59,589
This new life will
follow these pre-programmed

18
00:00:59,589 --> 00:01:03,026
instructions to grow
and develop into a human baby,

19
00:01:03,026 --> 00:01:05,161
and eventually a full-grown adult.

20
00:01:05,161 --> 00:01:10,166
Science has shown that birth changes
where the child is, not what the child is.

21
00:01:10,166 --> 00:01:15,538
Psalm 139:13-14
reads, "For you formed my inward parts.

22
00:01:15,538 --> 00:01:17,974
You knitted me
together in my mother's womb.

23
00:01:17,974 --> 00:01:21,911
I praise you, for I am
fearfully and wonderfully made."

24
00:01:21,911 --> 00:01:23,880
I love it when
science catches up with the Bible.

25
00:01:23,880 --> 00:01:25,314
Yeah, me too.

